        "text": "A few organizations were allowed to keep working on radio during the war.  Westinghouse ([[Westinghouse Electric Corporation]]) was the most well-known of these.  [[Frank Conrad]], a Westinghouse engineer, had been making transmissions from 8XK since 1916 that included music programming.[http://www.ieee.org/web/aboutus/history_center/biography/conrad.html Frank Conrad The Father of Commercial Broadcasting] A team at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]] headed by Professor [[Earle M. Terry]] was also on the air.[https://books.google.com/?id=nKFvnNl9vOEC&pg=PA39&lpg=PA39&dq=earle+m+terry#PPA72,M Reference to Earle M.Terry in a History of Broadcasting in the United States]  They operated 9XM ([[WHA (AM)]]), originally licensed by Professor Edward Bennett ([[Edward Bennett (physicist)]]) in 1914, and experimented with voice broadcasts starting in 1917."
